description:
Large reasoning models (LRMs) rely on long-chain reasoning to improve performance in complex tasks, but this introduces redundant reasoning paths and structurally redundant computational problems. Existing methods mainly reduce redundancy through length penalties or external control mechanisms, lacking a theoretical characterization of the "reasoning structure itself."  
 &nbsp; 
  This paper proposes a novel training paradigm: Matroid-Constrained Reasoning Optimization (MCR&sup2;O). This method introduces Matroid Theory into reasoning trajectory modeling for the first time, treating the model-generated reasoning steps as a set of elements satisfying independence constraints, and defining the effective reasoning process as a "basis" in the matroid.  
 &nbsp; 
  We construct a "reasoning matroid system," defining the independence of reasoning steps, the rank function, and a greedy optimizable structure, thereby transforming the reasoning process into a combinatorial optimization problem with provably greedy optimal solutions. Based on this, we propose a training objective based on matroid constraints, enabling the model to automatically learn the "minimum sufficient reasoning substructure."  
 &nbsp; 
  This paradigm can achieve structural redundancy removal reasoning without external pruning and provides a new "structurally controllable reasoning theoretical foundation" for LRM.

